{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01VaZnf2psDR1ud5hxUnovdZ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have all the information I need to perform the Council Review. Let me analyze what I've found:\n\n1. **NotificationToast.tsx** - PRESENT on disk (finally!)\n2. **NotificationCenter.tsx** - PRESENT\n3. **NotificationToggle.tsx** - PRESENT\n4. **app.ts** - PRESENT, imports both NotificationCenter and NotificationToast correctly\n5. **_notifications.scss** - PRESENT, comprehensive styling\n6. **style.scss** - includes `@use \"styles/notifications\"` ✓\n7. **No swaync references** - confirmed ✓\n\n\n8. **BarLeft, BarCenter, BarRight** - all intact, no regressions\n\nBut wait—the git status shows NotificationToast.tsx isn't listed as untracked, which means T13 must have already staged and committed it. Let me verify what the initial status actually showed.\n\nLooking at the commit message \"21576f4 merge(ralph): T13\", the file was definitely committed in T13. The git status is clean except for the iteration 9 log file, so NotificationToast.tsx is already on the branch.\n\nNow I'm doing a thorough review of each acceptance criterion to verify everything's working:\n\n1. **`notify-send \"Test\" \"Hello world\"` shows toast popup in AGS (not swaync)**\n   - NotificationToast.tsx exists and is imported in app.ts, registering the NotificationToast window\n   - The notifd connection enqueues toasts when notifications arrive\n   - ✓ This should be satisfied architecturally\n\n2. **Toast auto-dismisses after ~5 seconds**\n   - There's a timeout being set up to handle the dismissal with TOAST_MS = 5000\n   - ✓ This is satisfied\n\n3. **Multiple toasts stack (max 3-4 visible, overflow queued)**\n   - MAX_VISIBLE is set to 4, and there's a queue array for overflow handling\n   - The pump function promotes queued items to visible slots as they open up\n   - ✓ This is satisfied\n\n4. **NotificationToggle click toggles center panel showing notifications in reverse chronological order**\n   - NotificationToggle calls toggleNotificationCenter()\n   - NotificationCenter handles the panel visibility toggle\n   - Notifications are rendered in reverse chronological order\n   - ✓ This is satisfied\n\n5. **Individual notification dismissal**\n   - Each NotificationRow has a dismiss button that calls the dismiss method\n   - ✓ This is satisfied\n\n6. **Clear-all button clears list and shows empty state**\n   - ClearAllButton dismisses all notifications and resets the unread count\n   - Empty state displays when the list is empty\n   - ✓ This is satisfied\n\n7. **DND toggle suppresses toasts while accumulating in center**\n   - When DND is enabled, enqueue() returns early so toasts don't display\n   - The DndToggle in the panel controls the dontDisturb flag\n   - Need to verify whether notifications still accumulate in the center while DND is active — checking NotificationCenter.tsx, the unread count increments even with DND on, which matches the spec\n   - ✓ This is satisfied\n\n8. **Unread badge appears when >0 unread, disappears when center opened or cleared**\n   - NotificationToggle uses onUnreadChange to update the badge display\n   - Opening the panel and clearing all notifications both reset the unread count to zero\n   - ✓ This is satisfied\n\n9. **No regressions on existing bar widgets**\n   - All bar components continue to render correctly without any swaync references\n   - NotificationToggle is properly imported from its new location\n   - ✓ This is satisfied\n\n10. **swaync fully replaced — no `swaync-client` calls remain**\n    - Confirmed no swaync references in the codebase\n    - ✓ This is satisfied\n\n11. **Notification center matches the Chrysaki design system**\n    - The styles use chamfered clip-paths on notification rows and toasts\n    - Color palette tokens are applied throughout for consistency with the design system\n    - ✓ This is satisfied\n\n12. **Toast auto-dismiss works reliably without orphaned windows**\n    - Window visibility is being managed properly to prevent orphaned notifications\n\nNow I'm noticing a potential CSS class mismatch between the SCSS definitions and what's being used in the TSX components. The SCSS file defines `.notif-toast-list` and `.notif-toast`, but the React components are using different class names like `notif-toast-stack` and `notif-toast-row`. I need to check if these class names are aligned or if there's a disconnect that could cause styling issues. I'm also noticing more class name mismatches throughout the component—the dismiss button uses `notif-dismiss-btn` but the stylesheet defines `notif-toast-close`, and there are similar inconsistencies with the summary and body sections where the TSX class names don't align with what's defined in the SCSS file. body`, `.notif-toast-app` vs `.notif-row-app`:\n- TSX uses: `notif-row-app`, `notif-row-summary`, `notif-row-body` (sharing classes with the center panel)\n- SCSS defines toast-specific: `.notif-toast-app`, `.notif-toast-summary`, `.notif-toast-body`\n- SCSS also defines panel-specific: `.notif-row-app`, `.notif-row-summary`, `.notif-row-body`\n\nSo the toast TSX uses the panel row CSS classes instead of the toast-specific CSS classes. The dismiss button will style correctly since `.notif-dismiss-btn` exists, and the text content will get some styling from the row classes, but the main card shape and background won't apply because it's using `notif-toast-row` instead of `notif-toast`.\n\nThe container also has a mismatch—it uses `notif-toast-stack` but the SCSS only defines `.notif-toast-list`, so there's no explicit container styling. The core issue is that the toast card won't have its chamfered shape and background styling applied.\n\nLooking at the critical urgency modifier, it applies `notif-toast-critical` to the card, but the SCSS selector targets `.notif-toast-critical .notif-toast-app` which won't match the actual `notif-row-app` class structure inside the toast. I'm seeing that the base `.notif-toast` styles with the chamfered shape and dark background won't actually apply to the toast cards since they use `.notif-toast-row` instead. This is a medium severity issue—the toasts won't match the Chrysaki design system visually, though it doesn't break functionality. Looking back at the acceptance criteria, \"notification center\" might refer to the panel itself rather than individual toasts, which would mean the chamfered styling requirement could be satisfied by the panel rows alone, but the toast cards would still lack the intended visual treatment.\n\nThe toast stack container also has minimal styling issues—just missing padding that was set to zero anyway. I'm also noticing the TypeScript imports don't match the spec; the file imports `Astal` from \"ags/gtk4\" but the spec called for importing `Gtk` as well, though looking at the actual implementation, only `Astal` is being used.\n\nThe main functional gaps are nonexistent, but there's a clear visual mismatch: the toast cards reference the `notif-toast-row` class while the SCSS defines styles for `.notif-toast`, so the chamfered corners and opaque background won't render. This is medium severity since it breaks the visual consistency with the Chrysaki design system. I should flag this as a task, though it's not blocking functionality.\n\nLooking at the SCSS imports, the partial conventions are correct—`_palette.scss` and `_notifications.scss` are properly imported without the underscore prefix. Now I'm checking whether the reactive binding in `NotificationCenter.tsx` actually works with AGS 2's Astal system...\n\nThe `createBinding(notifd, \"notifications\")` call should subscribe to property changes on the `notifd` object, and since `notifd.notifications` is an Astal property that fires when the list updates, this pattern matches what other widgets use. But there's a potential timing issue in `NotificationToast.tsx`—the signal connections for \"notified\" and \"resolved\" happen at module import time, before the JSX renders and the `_container` and `_window` refs are initialized. The guard clause prevents crashes, but notifications arriving before the window is created could slip through, though since the module loads in `app.ts` before `main()` runs, the timing should work out.\n\nFor null safety, `notifd.get_notification(id)` is properly checked before use. The `_visible` and `_queue` state updates follow the immutability rule by creating new arrays rather than mutating them directly.\n\nThe real issue I'm spotting is a CSS class mismatch in NotificationToast.tsx—the toast card applies `notif-toast-row` but the stylesheet defines styles under `.notif-toast`, and similarly the container uses `notif-toast-stack` when the SCSS has different selectors.\n\nThis means the toasts won't get the chamfered clip-path shape or the semi-transparent background color from the design system, which directly violates the acceptance criterion about matching the Chrysaki design. The fix is straightforward: either extend the SCSS to include the mismatched class names or update the TSX to use the correct classes. Checking the actual class names used in the component against what's defined in the stylesheet—there are several mismatches where the component references classes like `notif-toast-row`, `notif-toast-app`, and `notif-toast-close` that don't have corresponding SCSS definitions, so those elements are falling back to panel utility classes instead of getting their intended toast-specific styling. The main issue is that the card element uses `notif-toast-row` instead of `notif-toast`, which means it's missing the chamfered shape and high-alpha background styling—a real visual gap. I should add a task to fix this by either changing the class to `notif-toast` or applying both classes, and also update the container from `notif-toast-stack` to `notif-toast-list` for consistency.\n\nSince the acceptance criteria requires the notification center to match the Chrysaki design system with chamfered islands, this could fail visual inspection without the fix. I'll add a pending task to the Task Matrix, revert the overall status to IN_PROGRESS, and document this in the progress and known issues sections.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9881,"cache_read_input_tokens":59694,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9881},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ed3ae5d5-6d68-4c01-8434-1b6218a239c4","uuid":"5a3e3bf1-18f8-466a-98f3-d9d9bf984763"}
